===Etymology===
From {{inh|en|enm|welcome}}, {{m|enm|wolcume}}, {{m|enm|wulcume}}, {{m|enm|wilcume}}, from {{inh|en|ang|wilcuma}} {{gloss|“a wished-for guest”; compare also {{m|ang|wilcume|t=welcome!|pos=interjection}}}}, from {{inh|en|gem-pro|*wiljakumô|t=a comer, a wished-for guest}}, equivalent to {{compound|en|will|t1=desire|come|t2=comer, arrival}}. The component ''wil-'' was replaced by ''wel-'' when the sense “guest” of the second component was no longer understood, possibly under the influence of fm+|fr|bienvenu}}FUCKFUCKFUCKFUCKFUCKFUCKFUCKFUCKFUCKFUCK. Cognate with {{cog|sco|walcome|t=welcome}}, {{cog|fy|wolkom|t=welcome}}, {{cog|nl|welkom|t=welcome}} (earlier ''willecome''), {{cog|de|willkommen|t=welcome}}, Danish and Norwegian {{m|da|velkommen|t=welcome}}, Swedish {{m|sv|välkommen|t=welcome}}, {{cog|is|velkomin|t=welcome}}, {{cog|fo|vælkomin|t=welcome}}, Low Saxon: ''willkamen''.

Similar constructions are common in [[Romance languages]], such as Italian {{m|it|benvenuto}}, Spanish {{m|es|bienvenido}}, French {{m|fr|bienvenu}}, Catalan {{m|ca|benvingut}}, Portuguese {{m|pt|bem-vindo}} and Romanian {{m|ro|bun venit}}, each meaning “[may you have fared] well [in] coming [here]”. These do not derive from Classic Latin, where a similar construction is not found, and presumably are instead the result of a calque from, considering the ruling elite of the barbarian kingdoms which succeeded the {{w|Western Roman Empire}}, a Germanic language to Proto-Romance (Vulgar Latin; see {{cog|la|*bene venutus}}, and compare {{m|la|*perdono}} for similar historical phenomenon).

